<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MUSIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Expecting to hear the opening of Brahms' Violin Concerto, Music Director Andre 
Previn raised his arms Thursday to begin his morning rehearsal with the Los 
Angeles Philharmonic. What did he hear? The familiar strains of "Happy Birthday 
to You," as played by 100-plus members of the orchestra. Thursday was Previn's 
60th birthday -- he was born in Berlin, April 6, 1929 -- and the date was not 
overlooked by his Philharmonic colleagues. At the break following the Brahms 
rehearsal, Previn, violin soloist Joshua Bell and the orchestra enjoyed 
birthday cake. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
