<TEXT>
<P>
Senate sponsors of legislation to raise the minimum wage ignored President 
Bush's veto threat and pressed ahead with a plan to boost the hourly base wage 
to $4.55 -- 30 cents more than Bush has said he would agree to. The bill's 
sponsor, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.), won vital Southern Democratic 
support by agreeing to cut the final target of his bill from $4.65 an hour to 
$4.55 and add a provision allowing workers to be paid a sub-minimum wage for 
their first two months in the job market. Those changes are likely to be 
offered by Southern Democratic senators today. The agreement appears to give 
Kennedy more than enough votes to win passage of his plan, although a final 
vote likely will not come until next week. 
