<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Truth in Pasta: Traditional Italian pasta will get a special quality-control 
mark from the Italian government under a measure aimed at helping consumers 
distinguish it from cheaper imported mixed-wheat pasta. The measure, approved 
by the nation's Cabinet and expected to take effect this year, will force 
foreign pasta makers to list their ingredients on packages they want to sell in 
Italy. Even diners in restaurants will have to be notified of the type of pasta 
they are eating. In July, the European Community Court of Justice overturned an 
Italian law that barred the sale of pasta not made entirely with durum wheat. 
</P>
