<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
RESTART OF RANCHO SECO APPROVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said today it will not interfere with plans 
for restarting the troubled Rancho Seco nuclear power plant near Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
The commission's action came after a briefing by the staff in which it said it 
disagreed with the conclusion of a private industry watchdog group that recent 
troubles at the plant were the result of pressure to avoid a required shutdown 
if it did not operate enough. 
</P>
<P>
Victor Stello, the commission's executive director for operations, told the 
commission that if it did not object, "it would be our intention to allow the 
restart of" the 913-megawatt plant operated by the Sacramento Municipal Utility 
District. 
</P>
</TEXT>
